Introduction

The dataset comprises health and lifestyle information for 200 individuals, with the key outcome variable being blood pressure (bp). The variables included are id, age, height, weight, cholesterol, smoke, and exercise. The dataset aims to investigate the relationship between blood pressure and other factors such as age, height, weight, cholesterol levels, smoking status, and exercise frequency. Understanding these relationships can help in identifying potential risk factors and lifestyle influences on blood pressure, thereby contributing to better health management and intervention strategies.

Data comes will labelled variable.

We can convert those variables to factor variables:

dat.o <- 
  dat.o %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.labelled), ~as_factor(.x)))
summary(dat.o)

We will use cut() function to create a categorical (factor) outcome variable. Variable bp will be categorized into a 4 category variable bp4.

Then we use the label() function to label the variable.

dat.o <- dat.o %>%
  mutate(bp4 = cut(bp, 
                   breaks = c(-Inf, 120, 140, 160, Inf),
                   labels = c('=<120','121-140','141-160','>160'),
                   right = TRUE))

Let us check if we have grouped correctly:

# Summarizing the min and max of 'bp' for each 'bp4' group
dat.o %>%
  select(bp4, bp) %>%
  group_by(bp4) %>%
  summarize(
    min_bp = min(bp, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_bp = max(bp, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
## # A tibble: 4 × 3
##   bp4     min_bp max_bp
##   <fct>    <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 =<120       91    120
## 2 121-140    121    140
## 3 141-160    141    160
## 4 >160       161    179

Next, we will used ordered function to create an ordinal variable and define the levels of the variable.

We will reverse the order of the outcome variable.

lev <- c('>160','141-160','121-140','=<120')
lev
## [1] ">160"    "141-160" "121-140" "=<120"
dat.o <- dat.o %>% 
  mutate(bp4a = fct_relevel(bp4, lev)) %>%
  mutate(bp4a = ordered(bp4a, levels = lev))

Let us check if we have done correctly:

str(dat.o$bp4a)
##  Ord.factor w/ 4 levels ">160"<"141-160"<..: 4 2 1 3 1 4 4 3 1 2 ...
levels(dat.o$bp4)
## [1] "=<120"   "121-140" "141-160" ">160"
table(dat.o$bp4)
## 
##   =<120 121-140 141-160    >160 
##      66      40      44      50
levels(dat.o$bp4a)
## [1] ">160"    "141-160" "121-140" "=<120"
table(dat.o$bp4a)
## 
##    >160 141-160 121-140   =<120 
##      50      44      40      66

Exploratory Data Analysis

Histogram of Age by Blood Pressure Category

# Histogram of age by blood pressure category
p1 <- ggplot(dat.o, aes(x = age, fill = bp4)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "dodge", alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~ bp4, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Age by Blood Pressure Category",
       x = "Age",
       y = "Count",
       fill = "Blood Pressure Category") +
  theme_minimal()

summary_table <- dat.o %>%
  select(bp4, age, height, weight, cholesterol, smoke, exercise) %>%
  tbl_summary(
    by = bp4,
    statistic = list(
      all_continuous() ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      all_categorical() ~ "{n} ({p}%)"
    ),
    type = list(
      where(is.logical) ~ "categorical"
    ),
    label = list(
      age ~ "age", 
      height ~ "height (cm)", 
      weight ~ "weight (kg)", 
      cholesterol ~ "cholesterol (mmol/L)", 
      smoke ~ "smoke", 
      exercise ~ "exercise"
    ),
    missing_text = "Missing"
  ) %>%
  modify_caption("**Table 1. Participant Characteristics by Blood Pressure Group**") %>%
  modify_header(label ~ "**Variable**") %>%
  modify_spanning_header(
    starts_with("stat_") ~ "**Blood Pressure Group**"
  ) %>%
  modify_footnote(all_stat_cols() ~ "Mean (SD) or Frequency (%)") %>%
  bold_labels() %>%
  as_gt()

# Print the summary table
print(summary_table)

Estimation

Adjacent-category model or multinomial or baseline logit model

Here, we will show how to replicate the baseline logit model (unconstrained). We could not reproduce the adjancent-category models that is based on constrained logit models.

Generate a new variable but with no ordering

dat.o <- 
  dat.o %>% 
  mutate(bp4b = fct_relevel(bp4, lev))

Run the mlogit 

mlogit1 <- 
  vglm(bp4 ~ exercise, multinomial, data = dat.o)
summary(mlogit1)
##

And get the RRR

exp(coef(mlogit1))
## (Intercept):1 (Intercept):2 (Intercept):3    exercise:1    exercise:2 
##     1.2734648     0.8939387     0.8166777     1.0175934     0.9455365 
##    exercise:3 
##     1.0366114
# Function to calculate confidence intervals for log odds and exponentiate them for RRR
calc_ci_rrr <- function(estimate, stderr) {
  log_rrr_ci_lower <- estimate - 1.96 * stderr
  log_rrr_ci_upper <- estimate + 1.96 * stderr
  rrr_ci_lower <- exp(log_rrr_ci_lower)
  rrr_ci_upper <- exp(log_rrr_ci_upper)
  return(c(rrr_ci_lower, rrr_ci_upper))
}

# Create data frames for coefficient estimates and RRR
coefficients <- data.frame(
  Term = c("(Intercept):1", "(Intercept):2", "(Intercept):3", "exercise:1", "exercise:2", "exercise:3"),
  Estimate = c(0.24174, -0.11212, -0.20251, 0.01744, -0.05600, 0.03596),
  StdError = c(0.32800, 0.36160, 0.36472, 0.13094, 0.14812, 0.14449),
  ZValue = c(0.737, -0.310, -0.555, 0.133, -0.378, 0.249),
  PValue = c(0.461, 0.757, 0.579, 0.894, 0.705, 0.803)
)

rrr <- data.frame(
  Term = c("(Intercept):1", "(Intercept):2", "(Intercept):3", "exercise:1", "exercise:2", "exercise:3"),
  RRR = c(1.2734648, 0.8939387, 0.8166777, 1.0175934, 0.9455365, 1.0366114)
)

# Calculate CIs for RRR and combine the data frames
combined_table <- coefficients %>%
  mutate(CI_RRR = purrr::map2(Estimate, StdError, calc_ci_rrr)) %>%
  tidyr::unnest_wider(CI_RRR, names_sep = "_") %>%
  rename(CI_RRR_Lower = CI_RRR_1, CI_RRR_Upper = CI_RRR_2) %>%
  left_join(rrr, by = "Term")

# Print the combined table in a tidy format
kable(combined_table, format = "pipe", caption = "Combined Coefficients and RRR Table with Confidence Intervals")

Continuation-ratio

To perform a continuation-ratio analysis similar to the example you provided but for the bp4 variable, we need to create three comparisons:

  1. Compare bp4 == >160 vs. bp4 == 141-160

  2. Compare bp4 == >160 and bp4 == 141-160 vs. bp4 == 121-140

  3. Compare bp4 == >160 and bp4 == 141-160 and bp4 == 121-140 vs. bp4 == =<120

    1. Compare bp4 == >160 vs. bp4 == 141-160
    table(dat.o$bp4) ; table(dat.o$bp4a)
    ## 
##   =<120 121-140 141-160    >160 
##      66      40      44      50
    ## 
##    >160 141-160 121-140   =<120 
##      50      44      40      66
dat.oa <- 
  dat.o %>% 
  filter(bp4 == '>160' | bp4 == '141-160')
cr1 <- glm(bp4a ~ exercise, family = binomial(link ='logit'),
           data = dat.oa)
summary(cr1)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = bp4a ~ exercise, family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
##     data = dat.oa)
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)
## (Intercept) -0.20414    0.36742  -0.556    0.578
## exercise     0.03674    0.14607   0.252    0.801
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 129.93  on 93  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 129.87  on 92  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 133.87
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 3

  1. Compare bp4 == >160 and bp4 == 141-160 vs. bp4 == 121-140

    For this we will recode variable bp using ifelse function. Please, make sure the code will be 0 and 1. using code bigger will not make glm function work

dat.ob <- dat.o %>% 
  filter(bp4 == '>160' | 
         bp4 == '141-160'| 
         bp4 == '121-140')
table(dat.ob$bp4a)
## 
##    >160 141-160 121-140   =<120 
##      50      44      40       0
dat.ob <- dat.ob %>% 
  mutate(bp4b = ifelse(bp4a == ">160", 0, 
                        ifelse(bp4a == "141-160",0,1)))
table(dat.ob$bp4a) ; table(dat.ob$bp4b)
## 
##    >160 141-160 121-140   =<120 
##      50      44      40       0
## 
##  0  1 
## 94 40

  glm(bp4c ~ exercise, family = binomial(link = 'logit'),

# Function to calculate confidence intervals
calc_ci <- function(estimate, stderr) {
  lower <- estimate - 1.96 * stderr
  upper <- estimate + 1.96 * stderr
  return(c(lower, upper))
}

# Create data frames for each model's results and calculate CI
cr1_results <- data.frame(
  Model = "cr1",
  Term = c("(Intercept)", "exercise"),
  Estimate = c(-0.20414, 0.03674),
  StdError = c(0.36742, 0.14607),
  ZValue = c(-0.556, 0.252),
  PValue = c(0.578, 0.801)
) %>% mutate(CI = purrr::map2(Estimate, StdError, calc_ci)) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest_wider(CI, names_sep = "_")

cr2_results <- data.frame(
  Model = "cr2",
  Term = c("(Intercept)", "exercise"),
  Estimate = c(-0.70597, -0.07423),
  StdError = c(0.32332, 0.13317),
  ZValue = c(-2.184, -0.557),
  PValue = c(0.029, 0.577)
) %>% mutate(CI = purrr::map2(Estimate, StdError, calc_ci)) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest_wider(CI, names_sep = "_")

cr3_results <- data.frame(
  Model = "cr3",
  Term = c("(Intercept)", "exercise"),
  Estimate = c(-0.75411, 0.02237),
  StdError = c(0.26352, 0.10501),
  ZValue = c(-2.862, 0.213),
  PValue = c(0.00421, 0.83130)
) %>% mutate(CI = purrr::map2(Estimate, StdError, calc_ci)) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest_wider(CI, names_sep = "_")

# Combine the data frames
combined_results <- bind_rows(cr1_results, cr2_results, cr3_results) %>%
  rename(CI_Lower = CI_1, CI_Upper = CI_2)

# Print the combined table in a tidy format
kable(combined_results, format = "pipe", caption = "Combined Logistic Regression Results with Confidence Intervals")

The mean of the estimates is approximately 0.01702, which is close to 0.02.

  • The standard deviation is approximately 0.01866, indicating the estimates are spread around the mean by this amount.

  • The range of the estimates is 0.04478, indicating the difference between the highest and lowest estimate.

Considering the mean and standard deviation, we can conclude that the estimates are relatively close to each other and are centered around 0.02.

These estimates are relatively close to each other and are centered around 0.02. This suggests that the impact of exercise frequency on the odds of being in a higher blood pressure category compared to a lower one is quite consistent and not very strong. Specifically, the odds of being in a higher blood pressure category is about 1.02=exp(0.02) for those who do not exercise compared who exercise.

Cumulative link logit model

This is also known as the proportional odds model.

Cumulative Logit Models (Proportional Odds Models) Another example of proportional odds models. We use the the variables that code from the lowest bo (=<120) to the highest bp (>160)

# Load necessary library

# Calculate mean blood pressure for each category of bp4
mean_bp_by_category <- dat.o %>%
  group_by(bp4) %>%
  summarize(mean_bp = mean(bp, na.rm = TRUE))

# Display the result
print(mean_bp_by_category)
## # A tibble: 4 × 2
##   bp4     mean_bp
##   <fct>     <dbl>
## 1 =<120      106.
## 2 121-140    132.
## 3 141-160    150.
## 4 >160       170.

Recheck the levels to confirm that from smallest category of bp to highest bp.

For the bp4 categories, the mean blood pressure values are as follows:

  • bp4 (=<120): mean blood pressure = 106.2

  • bp4 (121-140): mean blood pressure = 132.3

  • bp4 (141-160): mean blood pressure = 150.2

  • bp4 (>=160): mean blood pressure = 170.3

In Stata for example, the way we treat cumulative link logits is similar (not similar in the estimation process, just the context) to ordinal linear regression. That is we estimate how big the increase in the outcome variable with every unit increase in the predictor.

levels(dat.o$bp4)
## [1] "=<120"   "121-140" "141-160" ">160"

The variables:

  1. outcome = bp4

  2. covariate = age

Interpretation

The coefficient β̂age=0.013514 . This shows that the older the age, then the value of bp also increases.

For every 1-year increase in age, the odds of being in a higher blood pressure category decrease by about 1.3%.

For every 10-year increase in age, the odds of being in a higher blood pressure category decrease by about 12.2%.

exp(1 * -0.013)
## [1] 0.9870841
exp(10 * -0.013514)
## [1] 0.8735936

For every 1-year increase in age, the odds of being in a lower blood pressure category is 1.01 or increased for 1%.

For every 10-year increase in age, the odds of being in a lower blood pressure category is 1.14 or increased for 14%.

exp(1 * 0.013)
## [1] 1.013085
exp(10 * 0.013514)
## [1] 1.144697

The coefficients for model o.age

coef.o.age<- coef(o.age)
coef.o.age
##   =<120|121-140 121-140|141-160    141-160|>160             age 
##     -0.06519330      0.77717232      1.77127756      0.01351378
age_value <- 32
lp.o1.bx <- coef.o.age['age'] * age_value

Putting them inside the equation

lp.o1.bx <- 0.01351378 * 32
lp.o1.bx <- 0.432441

And complete the Eq 8.25 in Hosmer

logit1 <- coef.o.age['=<120|121-140'] - lp.o1.bx
logit2 <- coef.o.age['121-140|141-160'] - lp.o1.bx
logit3 <- coef.o.age['141-160|>160'] - lp.o1.bx

Then the probabilities are

pLeq1 <- 1 / (1 + exp(-logit1))  # p(Y <= first threshold)
pLeq2 <- 1 / (1 + exp(-logit2))  # p(Y <= second threshold)
pLeq3 <- 1 / (1 + exp(-logit3))  # p(Y <= third threshold)

pLeq1 <- 1 / (1 + exp(0.4976343))  # = 0.3780968
pLeq2 <- 1 / (1 + exp(-0.3447313)) # = 0.5853394
pLeq3 <- 1 / (1 + exp(-1.3388366)) # = 0.7922986

pMat <- cbind(
  p1 = pLeq1,                   # Probability of being in the first category
  p2 = pLeq2 - pLeq1,           # Probability of being in the second category
  p3 = pLeq3 - pLeq2,           # Probability of being in the third category
  p4 = 1 - pLeq3                # Probability of being in the fourth category
)

pMat

dat.o <- dat.o %>%
  mutate(smoke = as.factor(smoke))

summary_table <- dat.o %>%
  select(bp4, age, height, weight, cholesterol, smoke, exercise) %>%
  tbl_summary(
    by = bp4,
    statistic = list(
      all_continuous() ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
      all_categorical() ~ "{n} ({p}%)"
    ),
    type = list(
      where(is.logical) ~ "categorical"
    ),
    label = list(
      age ~ "age", 
      height ~ "height (cm)", 
      weight ~ "weight (kg)", 
      cholesterol ~ "cholesterol (mmol/L)", 
      smoke ~ "smoke", 
      exercise ~ "exercise"
    ),
    missing_text = "Missing"
  ) %>%
  modify_caption("**Table 1. Participant Characteristics by Blood Pressure Group**") %>%
  modify_header(label ~ "**Variable**") %>%
  modify_spanning_header(
    starts_with("stat_") ~ "**Blood Pressure Group**"
  ) %>%
  modify_footnote(all_stat_cols() ~ "Mean (SD) or Frequency (%)") %>%
  bold_labels() %>%
  as_gt()

# Print the summary table
print(summary_table)

Intepretation

1. Adjacent-category model or multinomial or baseline logit model

Comparison of “>160” vs. “<=120”:

When increase in exercise, the log odds of having blood pressure “>160” compared to “<=120” changes by 0.02 (95% CI: (-0.23,0.27, p-value = 0.894). This indicates that exercise does not significantly affect the odds of being in the “>160” blood pressure category compared to “<=120”. The confidence interval is wide and includes 1, suggesting high uncertainty and that the true effect could be no change or even a decrease in risk.

Comparison of “141-160” vs. “<=120”:

When increase in exercise, the log odds of having blood pressure “141-160” compared to “<=120” changes by -0.06 (95% CI: (-0.35,0.23, p-value = 0.705). This indicates that exercise does not significantly affect the odds of being in the “141-160” blood pressure category compared to “<=120”. The confidence interval is wide, indicating a lack of precision in the estimate and that the true effect could range from a reduction to an increase in risk.

Comparison of “121-140” vs. “<=120”:

When increase in exercise, the log odds of having blood pressure “121-140” compared to “<=120” changes by 0.04 (95% CI: (-0.25,0.32, p-value = 0.803). This indicates that exercise does not significantly affect the odds of being in the “121-140” blood pressure category compared to “<=120”. The confidence interval is wide and includes 1, indicating that the true effect could be minimal or even in the opposite direction.

2. Plot of Predicted Probabilities of Blood Pressure Levels by Age Faceted by Smoke and Exercise

Age Effect
 Across all panels, the probability of having lower blood pressure (<=120) decreases with age, while the probability of having higher blood pressure (>160) increases with age.

Smoking Effect
Smokers (smoke: 1) generally have lower probabilities of lower blood pressure levels (<=120)
